bug.short_desc: Focus not being set on editor page change

long_desc.thetext:
Problem: Contact sensitive Help is not updated when user navigates between tabs in Transformation configuration editor. User has to press F1 again to receive the Help page that corresponds to the tab
Expected Result: Contact sensitive Help should be updated when user navigates between tabs in Transformation configuration editor.
I see the same behavior in the manifest editor. It may be that the dynamic assistance control isn't listening to the event (which would make it an eclipse UA issue).

Help view in the context-sensitive help mode should react to 'pageChanged' notification for IPageChangeProvider interface. I think that PDE manifest editor does implement this (actually, all UI Forms-based multi-page editors implement this interface). We should make sure this hasn't stopped working.

This is happening because the focus is not being set properly by the editor on page change. You can see the same problem by doing this:
- Open manifest editor - In overview, click the first field (ID) - Hit F1, note context help - Click on another view's tab, then back on the manifest editor's tab - Hit F1 again, no help
The editor should set focus to one of the fields inside the page when entering it. This is done for some pages (source pages), but not for others. You can either remember the last position like the source editors, or just go to the first field on the page.
I'm sending this to PDE to handle the manifest case. Originator, could you open a separate bug for the transformation editor? (I am not familiar with this one)

Patch: patch_158801_2006-09-29_11-01.txt Target: 3.3 M3
Patch released to HEAD
It appears that the focus from PDE form page controls is being taken away by the multi-page editor super-class on page changes and reassigned to the underlying page's control itself.
Work Done:
* Implemented feature to explicitly store the last control to have focus on a form page before a page change or the editor loses focus and restore the that focus after a page change or the editor gains focus
-> If the last control to have focus is a Text widget, its contents are selected (covers Bug #144494)
-> Implemented for all form pages belonging the following current editors (and applicable for future editors):
- Plug-in Manfiest - Build - Site - Product - Feature - Target - Schema - Simple Cheat Sheet
-> Programatically and recursively add focus listeners to a selected set of a form page's controls (Thanks to Curtis for the idea)
- Supported controls: Button, Combo, CCombo, Tree, Table, Spinner, Link, List, TabFolder, CTabFolder, Hyperlink, FilteredTree
-> Preserved bi-directional selection between the Plug-in Manifest editor's Extensions and Extension Points form pages and the Plug-in Manifest editor's plug-in.xml XML source pages
- Given higher priority
- Now focus gained in addition to preserved selection

bug.short_desc: Wrong {parameter} in CommonUIMessages.properties string

long_desc.thetext:
The FileModificationValidator_SaveProblemDialogMessage string in the CommonUIMessages.properties file in the org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.common.ui plug-in has a {1} instead of a {0}. This looks like a copy-and-paste mistake from the string above it, which does have a {0} also.
The result is that an NSL.bind() call in FileModificationValidator.okToSave() produces the string "<missing argument>" which is of no help to a user.
This can be fixed by changing {1} to {0} in all translations of the file, or by simply passing the argument twice to the NLS.bind().
Should investigate if this is related to Bug 159175 .
*** Bug 159175 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
Getting complains that users of the API do not know why the save request is failing. Attaching a simple patch.

Fixed in R1_0_maintenance

bug.short_desc: Provide builds of RCP platform for GMF editors

long_desc.thetext:
GMF Tooling should support RCP option and thus needs an RCP runtime to host generated code. This runtime consists of the following pieces: 1. Eclipse RCP + plugins required by GMF runtime such as org.eclipse.core.resources 2. EMF plugins that do not require Eclipse IDE 3. Draw2D, GEF, EMFT 4. GMF runtime without *.ide plugins
I suggest to provide zip files with all these plugins packaged in one distribution since: 1. They define what we mean under "RCP" term ))) 2. It takes time to figure out all the dependencies and pack such RCP runtime; it's error-prone and time-consuming process that should be automated

I'm not sure why this issue blocks 114200. As I see it, we need to create an org.eclipse.gmf.runtime.rcp-feature that lists the minimally required/included features/plug-ins. Providing a single bundle of these is easily handled by the build, but we'll need the list of the exact features/plug-ins to include (hence, the o.e.g.runtime.rcp-feature manifest), which should come as a result of your target config when generating a basic RCP-ish graphical diagram, right?
Similarly, we should provide this for the "lite" runtime.

I think that this request is a part of req described in 114200 and in this sense it "blocks" it but actually there is just a dependency. I thought that depends/blocks fields are ok to express this.
I'll enumerate required plugins.

Summary of problem for release note:

I believe that in this case, archives should always be hidden from the filter, i.e. not treated as folders. If the user wants to see the archives, she should add "*.zip", "*.jar" or whatever to the filetype matcher.

FYI, here's another stacktrace that might illustrate the problem better. Basically JSPJavaValidator (Worker-3) has a lock on the workspace and is trying to get a model. Meanwhile, BasicSearchQuery (Worker-6) has a lock on the model and is trying to get the workspace. Everyone else (like StructuredAutoEditStrategyJSP on the main UI thread) is trying to get the model, but cannot because worker-3 & worker-6 are waiting on each other.

Proposing this to be fixed for 1.5.2. This is a critical bug because all a user has to do is find occurrences in any file and then validate a jsp (jsp validation can be triggered by just saving a jsp file). Then the next time the user tries to perform any sort of action that requires getting a model on the UI (for example, just opening a new file in editor) everything will appear to be frozen.
The cause is summarized in comment #5.
The fix is summarized in comment #4 & comment #6. It's about a 1 line fix in 2 files, and the fix is for find occurrences to use a 1-file marker rule, rather than a workspace rule so that find occurrences & jsp java validation won't deadlock trying to get model & workspace while they're trying to perform their operation.

+1 I've reviewed this code and stack straces carefully with Amy, and think this is the best possible fix. And, perfectly safe, with no (little) chance of side effects. And, hangs of course are really really bad, and this hang is king of bad since I think to most users it will appear "random" and not so easy to see its related to search and validation in sequence.

bug.short_desc: [PATCH] Support for like-named annotations

long_desc.thetext:
Hibernate makes use of several annotations that have the same name (but different namespace) as their JPA counterparts. The existing teneo infrastructure will not function properly when trying to make use of these, instead always preferring one version of the annotation over the other. The attached patch allows for annotations to be prefixed, so that the two will be considered distinct.
@jpa:MapKey @hb:Mapkey
Perhaps MapKey isn't the best example since teneo doesn't (yet) support maps, but it is illustrative of the issue.
The associated patch alters how annotations are resolved by making use of the following example.
* When no prefix is specified, prefer JPA annotations over HB annotations. That is, first resolve the annotation in the JPA namespace. Then, if that didn't work, try to resolve it in the Hibernate namespace. * When a prefix is specified, only try to resolve the annotation within the indicated namespace.
The two prefixes/namespaces I've coded support for are "jpa:" and "hb:".
Note that this is a Hibernate-specific bit of functionality, although I'd assume that this type of thing may be valuable for JPOX, too.

bug.short_desc: Code Review for Java produces non-deterministic results

long_desc.thetext:
Created an attachment (id=50957) the patch
This patch eliminates the cache map in CodeReviewResource as the key is not deterministic, so the cache is error prone. This proposed patch has a couple of impacts on a cold start comparison. 1) The number of results remained the same at 31857. 2) Memory consumption of all "Code Review for Java" rules run on org.eclipse.jdt.core decreased by 37% from 410MB to 260MB 3) Unfortunately, the cost is an increase in analysis time because of the lack of a cache which increases the time by 44% from 3m 57s to 5m 41s.
A second run of the same analysis, consumed 60% of the memory of the first run at only 150MB and trimmed 10% of time off at only 5m 08s.

1) Explain why you believe this is a stop-ship defect. How does the defect manifest itself, and how will users of TPTP / consuming products be affected if the defect is not fixed?
When working with large-ish workspaces (which is the norm in commercial products) the result generate can poke completely bogus results into the output. In one example where 30,000 results were generated, 9,000 of them where compeltely invalid. With tiny workspaces of less than 100 classes this problem is rarely observed.
The patch for this also improves memory consumption by 50% at a slight cost in performance for large workspaces.
2) Is there a work-around? If so, why do you believe the work-around is insufficient?
No workaround. The user is currently at the mercy of the result generator.
3) Is this a regression or API breakage? Explain. Possibly a subtle regession related to a change made early in the 4.2 timeframe.
4) Does this require new API? No
5) Who performed the code review? Scott Cowan. Patches have been throughly tested
6) Is there a test case attached to the bugzilla record? No, the scenario that causes this problem is difficult to reproduce in a test because it typically involves running many rules on a very large workspace containing source code containing specific unpredictable patterns.
7) What is the risk associated with this fix? Minimal - slight performance degradation which will be addressed in 4.3
8) Is this fix related to any standards that TPTP adheres to? If so, who has validated that the fix continues to adhere to the standard? No

This patch only caches every query.
This approach returns the expected number of results 31857 with a peack RAM consumption of 427MB, a 4% degradation, in 4m 16s, a 10% time degredation.
